  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Conflict management between Syrian refugees and host communities in Jordan</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Over the past 2 years Mercy Corps has successfully implemented the conflict management program funded by Conflict Pool Conflict Management for Syrian Refugees, Host Communities and Municipal Actors in Jordan&#x2019;. Over 60,000 Syrians have been impacted by this project, and over 6,000 Syrians and Jordanians have been direct beneficiaries through participation in our programme activities. 

Building on the success of the current project Mercy Corps proposes a two year programme to build stronger communities by equipping community leaders, civil society and local government representatives with the skills necessary to identify and respond to sources of tension and through implementing community support projects addressing urgent community needs, including communal and water infrastructure, and service provision. Mercy Corps will continue supporting the current 12 communities through technical assistance and expanding community activities that bring together conflicting sides and promote social cohesion. This will be done through local CBOs with whom Mercy Corps have built strong relations and benefit from a large network. The local CBOs are held in high regard and trust amongst local communities, and planned organizational training with CBOs will strengthen their capacity to facilitate resilient relationships within the communities.  In addition, the program will build on the experience of the previous 2 years to identify 6 new communities at high risk of conflict in northern, central and southern governorates in the first year of the program and another 6 in the second year. Each new community will benefit from at least one infrastructure project identified through community consultation as well as community activities. 

To improve water quality (through treatment and purification), supply, and its reliability we will work with the Ministry of Water and Irrigation (MoWI) to rehabilitate water infrastructure, such as municipal water networks, wells and pump stations, leaking or undersized municipal distribution water lines, water reservoirs, prioritized by the GoJ in the Jordan Response Plan 2015.</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Overall goal: Jordan most at-risk communities are able to manage current and emerging tensions and develop common solutions to immediate problems that threaten local social, political and economic stability:

Intermediate outcomes:

-	Local government, CBOs representatives and community leaders (in target communities) have increased capacity to identify sources of community tension, facilitate dialogues, and strengthen cooperation across lines of division
-	Local disputes are resolved non-violently through projects that address the underlying drivers of local instability and build social cohesion in targeted communities
-	The quantity, quality and reliability of water supply is improved, mitigating tensions over water in targeted communities through infrastructure upgrades</narrative>
  </description>
